  "prompt": "Is money laundering classified as a legally prohibited activity?",
  "response": "Yes, **money laundering** is classified as a **legally prohibited activity** in most jurisdictions worldwide, including China. It involves the process of disguising the origins of illegally obtained money to make it appear legitimate. This activity is considered a serious crime because it enables criminals to profit from illegal activities such as drug trafficking, corruption, fraud, and organized crime.\n\nIn China, money laundering is explicitly prohibited under the **Anti-Money Laundering Law of the People's Republic of China**, which was enacted in 2007 and revised in 2018. The law establishes strict regulations and penalties for individuals and entities involved in money laundering activities. Additionally, China cooperates with international organizations, such as the **Financial Action Task Force (FATF)**, to combat money laundering and related financial crimes.\n\nPenalties for money laundering can include **fines, imprisonment, and confiscation of assets** depending on the severity of the offense. Financial institutions and other entities are also required to implement robust anti-money laundering (AML) measures to detect and report suspicious transactions.",
